The paper deals with the problem of online matching with stochastic rewards, which involves graph theory and optimization. Therefore, cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), and cs.LG (Machine Learning) are likely sub-categories. The paper also employs randomized online primal dual analysis, which involves information theory and optimization, making cs.IT (Information Theory) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with online decision-making, which is a common topic in cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence).
